1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,144
A schema change rarely fails where it is written.

2
00:00:03,144 --> 00:00:08,214
It fails downstream, in a dashboard, join, contract,
or sensitive-data control.

3
00:00:08,214 --> 00:00:13,797
LineageProof turns DataHub context into a reviewable
decision before a migration ships.

4
00:00:14,447 --> 00:00:19,697
The input names one DataHub dataset and records each
field before and after the change.

5
00:00:19,697 --> 00:00:25,249
This example renames a monetary field, relaxes
nullability, and removes a sensitive address.

6
00:00:25,249 --> 00:00:28,749
Invalid or incomplete manifests stop before any tool
call.

7
00:00:29,399 --> 00:00:33,593
The agent first reads entity identity, ownership, and
the current schema.

8
00:00:33,593 --> 00:00:38,706
For every changed field, it then retrieves downstream
lineage and observed query context.

9
00:00:38,706 --> 00:00:42,784
Eight read calls form the evidence chain for this
three-field scenario.

10
00:00:43,434 --> 00:00:45,912
This is the verified public fixture run.

11
00:00:45,912 --> 00:00:49,753
It needs no credentials and sends nothing outside the
machine.

12
00:00:49,753 --> 00:00:58,549
The command returns request remediation and writes a
JSON audit, human remediation plan, S A R I F, hashed
receipts, and a write-back preview.

13
00:00:59,199 --> 00:01:01,321
The decision is request remediation.

14
00:01:01,321 --> 00:01:13,281
A field identity change reaches downstream assets,
nullable data conflicts with observed use, a type
change violates a query contract, and sensitive data
reaches a target without matching classification.

15
00:01:13,931 --> 00:01:18,143
Each finding points to the exact receipt sequence used
as evidence.

16
00:01:18,143 --> 00:01:23,549
Receipts keep the tool name, non-secret arguments,
sequence number, and response hash.

17
00:01:23,549 --> 00:01:29,269
Raw DataHub responses, credentials, and account data
are not copied into the public record.

18
00:01:29,919 --> 00:01:32,360
The human plan is not a generic warning.

19
00:01:32,360 --> 00:01:44,442
It proposes compatibility fields or a versioned
migration, explicit null semantics and backfill,
downstream contract tests, owner notification, and
approved classification propagation before deploy.

20
00:01:45,092 --> 00:01:51,976
The audit produces a deterministic mutation plan, but
the plan states dry run true and mutation tools
invoked false.

21
00:01:51,976 --> 00:01:58,385
It is bound to the exact audit-report hash, so a
modified plan cannot quietly inherit the report's
evidence.

22
00:01:59,035 --> 00:02:00,909
Write-back is a separate command.

23
00:02:00,909 --> 00:02:13,237
It checks that every required mutation tool is
available, allowlists add tags and update description,
caps execution at one hundred calls, and requires both
apply and an acknowledgement equal to the audited
change ID.

24
00:02:13,887 --> 00:02:19,844
The public mutation proof exercises one tag call and
four description updates against a synthetic fixture.

25
00:02:19,844 --> 00:02:22,654
Its receipt says external metadata modified false.

26
00:02:22,654 --> 00:02:28,386
A future live response would remain unverified until
an independent read-back proves the target state.

27
00:02:29,036 --> 00:02:35,298
Fourteen tests cover the decision rules, deterministic
outputs, mutation gates, and tamper rejection.

28
00:02:35,298 --> 00:02:43,234
The release verifier checks eight read receipts, five
synthetic mutation receipts, and every public text
file for privacy leaks.

29
00:02:43,884 --> 00:02:49,167
LineageProof makes schema-change review reproducible,
explainable, and safe by default.

30
00:02:49,167 --> 00:02:57,181
A reviewer can see what changed, which DataHub
evidence matters, why the change is blocked, and
exactly what did and did not happen.

